that topline systems\nuse pretrained acoustic models (English [60], Tamil [61] and\n3 SPAM modeling at https://github.com/juice500ml/spam, evaluation at https:\n//github.com/stephenmac7/phone-metrics, and benchmark at https://github.com/ Thai [62]) that are trained on far more transcribed data than\nShikhar-S/Speech-Segmentation.\nSPAM. Furthermore, such systems are unavailable for many\n\n\fTABLE II\nP HONE RECOGNITION RESULTS (PFER ↓) ON THE PR I SM BENCHMARK [5]. S EE SECTION IV-B FOR DETAILS .\nAccented English Datasets\n\nMultilingual Datasets\n\nLearnable\nParam.\n\nPR-tmt [1]\n\nPR-arc [48]\n\nPR-saa [49]\n\nAvg.\n\nPR-drc [50]\n\nPR-vox [2]\n\nPR-tsm [6]\n\nAvg.\n\nToplines\nKoelLabs-XLSR [51]\nPhoneticXeus [16]\n\n300M\n580M\n\n9.6\n13.3\n\n7.8\n9.9\n\n7.8\n8.5\n\n8.4\n10.6\n\n22.9\n16.8\n\n18.0\n14.4\n\n24.7\n21.9\n\n21.9\n17.7\n\nTrained on TIMIT\nCTC\nFCE\n\n316M\n316M\n\n7.2\n8.7\n\n15.3\n18.9\n\n11.8\n15.8\n\n11.4\n14.5\n\n20.8\n26.4\n\n22.4\n40.2\n\n22.7\n35.9\n\n22.0\n34.2\n\nSPAM (Ours)\n\n47K\n\n22.9\n\n22.6\n\n23.4\n\n23.0\n\n27.3\n\n24.3\n\n35.0\n\n28.9\n\nModel\n\n26\n25\n24\n23\n22\n21\n\ncan incur the same loss. FCE, by contrast, imposes strong\nsupervision, which degrades sharply in the multilingual setting.\nInterestingly, SPAM maintains similar performance on both\n75\naccented English datasets and on TIMIT (PR-tmt), with\nTIMIT\nonly 2% relative degradation. CTC and FCE, by contrast,\n70\nVoxAngeles\nperform much better on the training data (TIMIT) but degrade\n1 1/22 1/24 1/26 1/28 1/210\n1 1/22 1/24 1/26 1/28 1/210\nby 60%–117% on accented English. This gap is even more\nData ratio\nData ratio\npronounced on multilingual datasets, where CTC and FCE\nFig. 3. Ablation on the training dataset size. We randomly subsample TIMIT degrade by 180%–360% while SPAM stays within 10%–50%.\ntraining split, which contains 4620 phonetically transcribed audio samples, These results suggest that gradient-based methods overfit to\nfrom the full 3 hours tra