E SEGMENTATION PERFORMANCE COMPARISON (R- VALUE ↑) ON\nDIFFERENT SIGNALS .\n\nFig. 4.\n\nVoxAngeles\n\n80\n60\n\nwav2vec 2.0\nXLS-R\nHuBERT\n20\nWavLM\n0 3 6 9 12 15 18 21 24 0 3 6 9 12 15 18 21 24\nLayer index\nLayer index\n40\n\nSegmentation performance on different S3Ms and layers for SPAM.\n\nD. Different S3Ms and layers ablations\nSettings. The 24th (final) layer of WavLM is known to be\nwell-suited for extracting phonological vectors [27], [28], so we\nuse it as our primary model and layer. However, since different\nmodels and layers encode phonetic information differently [32],\n[43], we sweep both. We compare four mainstream S3Ms with\nthe same number of transformer layers, wav2vec 2.0 [24],\nXLS-R [64], HuBERT [25], and WavLM [26].\nResults. Figure 4 shows that the final layer of WavLM achieves\nthe best R-value on both datasets, indicating that the quality\nof the phonological vectors directly affects SPAM and, in\nturn, downstream performance. Except for HuBERT, the layerwise trends are broadly similar across TIMIT and VoxAngeles,\nthough VoxAngeles amplifies the differences with sharper peaks\nand collapses. Comparing XLS-R against wav2vec 2.0 shows\nthat multilingual pretraining data does not guarantee better\nperformance. Note that the best model, WavLM, is Englishonly pretrained model.\n\nGround-truth segmentation. To localize the source of errors,\nwhether the recognizer or the segmenter, we replace the\npredicted boundaries with ground-truth segmentation, i.e., a\nperfect segmenter, and evaluate the recognition head alone.\nConcretely, we compare the baseline SPAM (predicted segmentation) against SPAM with ground-truth (GT) segmentation.\nGT segmentation lowers PFER substantially over the baseline\n(Table II): it more than halves the error on TIMIT (to 11.1)\nand cuts it to roughly a third on VoxAngeles (to 8.4). This\nindicates that the recognition head is already highly capable\nand that the segmenter is the primary bottleneck, hence being\nthe main target for further improvement.\nSeen and unseen phones. We further test whether SPAM\nrecognizes phones unseen during training as well as seen ones.\nOn VoxAngeles, we label each reference phone seen if it\nVI. D ISCUSSION\nappears in TIMIT and unseen otherwise, and measure PFER\nseparately on each group. We use GT segmentation, except Vocabulary filter. Qualitatively inspecting the predictions,\nthe silence segment, such that each GT phone corresponds to our model frequently outputs narrow (fine-grained) phonetic\nexactly one predicted phone. PFER is then 6.4 on seen phones transcriptions that reflect acoustic details. This is because the\nand 9.4 on unseen phones. Low PFER on unseen phones shows training-free prediction head is indifferent to how frequently\nthat SPAM recognizes unseen phones nearly as well as seen a phone occurs in training data. For usability, we add an\nones, likely due to the recognition head composing any phone optional vocabulary filter [40] that restricts the output to a\nknown inventory of each language.\ndirectly from its PanPhon features.\nTrainable extensions. Our method is fully differentiable, so the\nheads could be fine-tuned end-to-end. Also, the phonological\nC. Segmentation signal ablations\nfeatures, currently weighted uniformly, can be re-weighted via\nSettings. We verify whether ensembling (Section III-D) helps learnable parameters. We leave both to future work.\nand how each segmentation signal contributes. Start", "stderr": "\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false, "persistedOutputPath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/e6b331cd-d129-45d8-8d5b-06dbd4243734/tool-results/buef9vqhx.txt", "persistedOutputSize": 43791}}
