{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a319683eede68540", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tPhone Segmentation and Recognition through\n2\tPhonological Activation Mapping\n3\tShikhar Bharadwaj§∗ , Kwanghee Choi†∗ , Stephen McIntosh‡∗ , Chin-Jou Li§ , Eunjung Yeo† ,\n4\tDaisuke Saito‡ , Nobuaki Minematsu‡ , Shinji Watanabe§ , Jian Zhu¶ , David Harwath† and David R. Mortensen§\n5\t§ CMU, USA\n6\t\n7\t† UT Austin, USA\n8\t\n9\tarXiv:2607.09020v1 [eess.AS] 10 Jul 2026\n10\t\n11\t{sbharad2,dmortens}@andrew.cmu.edu\n12\t\n13\t‡ UTokyo, Japan\n14\t\n15\t{kwanghee,harwath}@utexas.edu\n16\t\n17\tAbstract—Phone segmentation and recognition are inherently\n18\trelated tasks, yet modern approaches typically model them\n19\tseparately. We argue that phonetic structure is already latent in\n20\tthe representations of self-supervised speech models (S3Ms), and\n21\tone only needs to steer them to solve both tasks. We leverage S3Mbased Phonological Activation Mapping (SPAM), which maps\n22\teach S3M representation frame to a vector of phonological feature\n23\tactivations, such as voicing and nasality. On top of SPAM, we\n24\tintroduce two simple but effective lightweight, gradient-descentfree prediction heads: a recognition head and a segmentation head.\n25\tOur method requires less than a minute of phonetic transcriptions,\n26\tand generalizes to unseen phones during training. Across a diverse\n27\trange of datasets, our approach attains strong segmentation and\n28\trecognition performance.\n29\tIndex Terms—phone segmentation, phone recognition, selfsupervised learning, phonetics, phonology\n30\t\n31\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n32\tPhones are the smallest independent units of speech sound,\n33\tconventionally transcribed across languages with the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA). Locating and recognizing\n34\tthem, i.e., phone segmentation and recognition, yields timealigned phonetic transcriptions [1], [2]. These are foundational\n35\tto a range of applications, including clinical assessment of\n36\tpathological speech, computer-assisted pronunciation training,\n37\tand the documentation of endangered languages [3]–[8].\n38\tHowever, obtaining such annotations is challenging, since\n39\texpert phonetic transcription is slow and costly. Annotating\n40\tone hour of speech can take a trained phonetician roughly 40\n41\tto 100 hours [9], [10]. Transcriptions can also be subjective,\n42\twith even experienced transcribers sometimes disagreeing on\n43\tphone labels and segment boundaries [11], [12].\n44\tThese challenges have motivated automatic phone recognition and segmentation models. Modern phone recognition is\n45\ttypically framed as a sequence-to-sequence task, much like\n46\tautomatic speech recognition (ASR) [13]–[16]. Accordingly,\n47\tit is often trained with a connectionist temporal classification\n48\t(CTC) loss [13], [17] or an attention-based encoder-decoder\n49\tarchitecture [15], [18], [19]. Phone segmentation, by contrast,\n50\tis typically cast as frame-wise classification [20]–[23], labeling\n51\teach frame as a boundary (1) or not (0). Yet for human listeners,\n52\tthe two are inseparable: hearing speech, we perceive both\n53\twhich phones are spoken and where they occur in time. This\n54\t∗ These authors contributed equally. Author order determined by random\n55\tshuffling.\n56\t\n57\t¶ UBC, Canada\n58\t\n59\t{smcintosh,mine}@gavo.t.u-tokyo.ac.jp\n60\t\n61\trt\n62\trt\n63\tProjected r t\n64\tProjected r t\n65\t\n66\tFig. 1. Overview of S3M-based Phonological Activation Mapping (SPAM).\n67\tLeft: Phonological vectors [27], [28] can be found in S3M representation\n68\tspace by taking the difference of means. For example, vvoi+ is the difference\n69\tbetween the mean representations of voiced phones and other phones.\n70\tRight: S3M frame representations rt and rt′ from different timesteps t\n71\tand t′ are projected onto phonological vectors [8], [28] (e.g., vback+ ),\n72\tyielding activation values (top right). Stacking these projections from different\n73\tphonological vectors for each frame produces a time-aligned activation mapping\n74\t(bottom right).\n75\t\n76\traises a natural question: can recognition and segmentation be\n77\taddressed through a unified representation?\n78\tWe argue that they can, since the representations of selfsupervised speech models (S3Ms) [24]–[26] already encode\n79\tsufficient information for both phone recognition and segmentation [27], [28]. In particular, S3M representation geometry\n80\tis dominated by phonetic information [25], [29]–[33].\n81\tTo isolate phonetic information, we turn to phonological\n82\tfeature decomposition [34]. Rather than treating each phone as\n83\tan atomic label, phonological features describe phones through\n84\tphysical descriptions such as the presence of voicing, tongue\n85\theight, and lip rounding. In this framework, a phone becomes\n86\ta vector of feature values. For example, [u] as in goose is\n87\trepresented as [voi+, hi+, back+, round+, ...].\n88\tPanPhon is a library that maps over 5,000 IPA segments to\n89\t21 such features [34].\n90\tRecent work [27], [28] shows that these phonological\n91\tfeatures can be accurately modeled as linear directions, i.e.,\n92\tphonological vectors, in the representation space of some\n93\tS3Ms. For instance, adding the voicing vector to a representation of [s] moves it toward [z] (Figure 1, left). Estimating\n94\tthese vectors is known to be highly sample-efficient [27],\n95\ta major practical advantage given the difficulties of expert\n96\tannotation. Projecting a frame’s S3M representation onto these\n97\t\n98\t\fvectors yields an activation value for each phonological feature\n99\t(Figure 1, top right). Stacking these phonological activations\n100\tover time results in an S3M-based Phonological Activation\n101\tMap [8], [28], or SPAM (Figure 1, bottom right). This produces\n102\ta time-aligned phonological representation of the speech.\n103\tWe design a segmentation head that locates phone boundaries through dissimilarity between adjacent phonological\n104\tactivations, inspired by prior work on acoustic and raw S3M\n105\trepresentations [35]–[37]. We also design a recognition head\n106\tbased on SPAM, which simply predicts phone identity at a\n107\tframe from its phonological activations. Accordingly, we can\n108\tpredict any cataloged phone in PanPhon, even if it does not\n109\texist in the training data.\n110\tWe claim that SPAMs have some key advantages for\n111\tphonetic tasks like segmentation and recognition. They are\n112\tbased on a naturally occurring representation subspace aligned\n113\twith human linguistic abstractions, which generalizes across\n114\tmany languages. Therefore, SPAM provides interpretability,\n115\tgeneralization and sample efficiency by design.\n116\tOur contributions are as follows:\n117\t• Novel segmentation and recognition methods. We\n118\tdesign two interpretable, lightweight, gradient-descentfree prediction heads that perform both tasks directly on\n119\tSPAM (Section III, Figure 2).\n120\t• Generalization and sample-efficiency. Our method needs\n121\tless than a minute of labeled data (Section V-A), recognizes phones never seen during training (Section V-C), and\n122\tgeneralizes well to low-resource languages and atypical\n123\tspeech (Section IV).\n124\t• Comprehensive evaluation. We benchmark across a\n125\twide array of datasets and languages, reflecting realistic\n126\tdownstream use cases (Section IV).\n127\tII. R ELATED WORK\n128\tSegmentation. Classic methods place boundaries at peaks\n129\tof frame-to-frame acoustic dissimilarity [35], with melspectrogram dissimilarity still a surprisingly strong baseline [38]. Recent works use learned representations such as\n130\tS3M [20] or self-supervised CPC [37], [39], and HMMs over\n131\tS3M features [38]. However, all stop at boundary detection,\n132\twhere we also explore phone recognition.\n133\tRecognition. Modern multilingual phonetic recognizers, such\n134\tas Allosaurus [40], Allophant [41], Wav2Vec2Phoneme [13],\n135\tZIPA [14], and PhoneticXeus [16], often learn a CTC,\n136\ttransducer, or encoder–decoder from large phone-transcribed\n137\tdatasets or grapheme-to-phoneme (G2P) pseudo-labels. Allophant is the closest to our recognition head, using articulatory\n138\tattributes. Ours, in contrast, is gradient-descent-free, choosing\n139\teach phone by matching its PanPhon feature vector against\n140\tSPAM, requiring much less data.\n141\tSegmentation and recognition. Chang and Glass [36] propose\n142\t“segmentation by recognition,” producing phone boundaries\n143\tthrough segment-based recognition rather than purely local\n144\tfeatures. More recent text-independent phone-to-audio alignment systems include Wav2Vec2-FC, Wav2Vec2-FS [21], and\n145\tTIPAA-SSL [42]. Wav2Vec2-FC uses frame-level cross-entropy\n146\t\n147\tRaw Audio\n148\t\n149\tTime (s)\n150\t\n151\tS3M\n152\t(Section III-A)\n153\t\n154\tS3M Features\n155\t\n156\tSPAM\n157\t\n158\tRecognizer (III-C)\n159\t\n160\tPhonological\n161\tVectors (III-B)\n162\t\n163\tSegmenter (III-D)\n164\tΔSPAM\n165\t\n166\tIPA\n167\t\n168\tPrediction\n169\t[0.00-0.14 _] [0.14-0.22 ʃ] [0.22-0.34 i]\n170\t\n171\tFig. 2.\n172\t\n173\tOverview of our method (Section III).\n174\t\n175\t(FCE), Wav2Vec2-FS uses forward-sum alignment without\n176\tframe-level labels (similar to CTC), and TIPAA-SSL combines\n177\tCTC with FCE. In contrast, we use no training loss, relying\n178\ton the phonetic structure SPAM already exposes.\n179\tIII. M ETHOD\n180\tA. S3M-based Phonological Vectors\n181\tS3M representation. A self-supervised speech model (S3M)\n182\tencodes a waveform into a sequence D dimensional frame-level\n183\trepresentations R = (r1 , . . . , rT ), where rt ∈ RD and T is\n184\tthe number of frames. These can be read from any transformer\n185\tlayer, although this choice matters since phonetic information\n186\tis distributed unevenly across layers [32]. Following [27], [28],\n187\twe primarily use the final layer of WavLM-large [26] for our\n188\texperiments, where we additionally ablate different models\n189\tand layers at Section V-D.\n190\tPooling. We extract a single vector for each phone, which\n191\ttypically spans several temporal frames, using center pooling:\n192\tthe phone is represented by the frame at the center rather\n193\tthan by averaging over the span [33], [43]. Center-pooled\n194\trepresentations are preferable for extracting phonological\n195\tvectors, as phonetic arithmetic [27] holds more reliably on\n196\tthem than on average-pooled representations [28], [31].\n197\tPhonological vectors. Recent work [27], [28] shows that,\n198\twithin an S3M’s representation space, each phonological feature\n199\tcan be effectively modeled as linear direction recoverable as\n200\ta difference of means. We use PanPhon [34] to assign each\n201\tphone its phonological features. Note that PanPhon uses a\n202\tternary feature system with +/0/−. + and − mark a property’s\n203\tpresence or absence (e.g., voiced versus voiceless), and 0 marks\n204\tthat the property does not apply to the phone (e.g., tenseness,\n205\twhich describes only vowels, is 0 for consonants).\n206\tWe split each ternary feature into two binary channels:\n207\tfeature+ and feature- [27], resulting in a set of phonological channels C. These are 1 when the feature is + or −,\n208\trespectively, and 0 otherwise. Pooling all training utterances,\n209\tlet Si denote the set of all phone segments where channel\n210\t\n211\t\fi ∈ C is 1 (i.e., active). We denote its complement by Si∁ . value for that phone, normalized by the number of active\n212\t∁\n213\tchannels (each canonical vector sums to 1). For each segment\n214\tFor example, Svoi+ contains all voiced segments, and Svoi+\n215\tcontains all other segments. We discard channels whose positive s delimited by the segmentation head (Section III-D), we read\n216\tt